Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while modern transformer models generate rich hierarchical representations across layers, current practices often underutilize this depth. Deep layers capture high-level semantics but may lose fine-grained syntactic structure, whereas shallow layers retain local dependencies and morpho-syntactic cues but lack compositional meaning. Prior work either uses layer-wise concatenation (e.g., ELMo), applies learned weighting (e.g., BERT-wwm), or injects syntax via auxiliary objectives (as in Paper 2), but none explicitly align shallow-layer syntactic scaffolding with deep-layer semantic embeddings in a structured fusion mechanism. Inspired by Papers 1 and 2—particularly their use of multi-level modeling and structural guidance—I propose a novel cross-layer fusion framework where syntactic information extracted from shallow transformer layers actively guides and enhances the refinement of semantic representations in deeper layers. Unlike retrofitting syntax post-hoc or using syntax as an auxiliary loss, my idea integrates syntax *during* representation fusion through attention modulation. This creates a dynamic, context-sensitive blending of structural and semantic knowledge. The key innovation lies in using self-extracted syntactic distance matrices from intermediate layers to gate and reweight deep-layer embeddings, forming a syntactically grounded yet semantically enriched sentence representation. This differs from existing methods by making syntax not just a side objective but a functional component of embedding composition. Furthermore, it avoids reliance on external parsers, ensuring end-to-end trainability and domain adaptability.

