  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces a novel architecture called 'Syntactically-Guided Semantic Enhancement via Cross-Layer Embedding Fusion in Transformers' (SG-SEF), which aims to improve sentence representation quality by strategically combining embeddings from both shallow and deep layers of a transformer model, guided by intrinsic syntactic structure. Rather than treating layer aggregation as a passive process (e.g., averaging or concatenating), SG-SEF leverages early-layer transformer activations to extract implicit syntactic distance patterns—such as constituent span likelihoods and dependency proximity—through a lightweight structure decoder. These syntactic priors are then used to modulate attention mechanisms in the fusion of deep-layer semantic embeddings. Specifically, we introduce a Cross-Layer Syntactic Attention (CLSA) module that takes shallow-layer hidden states and computes a differentiable syntactic affinity matrix, which is applied as a soft mask over the self-attention weights of aggregated deep-layer outputs. This allows syntactically coherent token groupings identified in lower layers to enhance contextual understanding in higher layers, effectively grounding abstract semantics in grammatical reality. To ensure compatibility across layers, we employ a bidirectional projection network that aligns dimensionalities and normalizes activation scales between shallow and deep representations. Additionally, during fine-tuning on downstream tasks, we incorporate a multi-task objective that jointly optimizes for semantic performance (e.g., classification accuracy) and syntactic consistency (measured via induced parse tree similarity against gold standards or probe-based evaluation). This dual objective reinforces the model’s ability to maintain structural integrity while enriching meaning. The approach is evaluated across diverse NLP tasks including sentence classification, paraphrase detection, textual entailment, and discourse coherence modeling, where strong syntactic-semantic alignment is crucial. We hypothesize that SG-SEF will outperform standard pooling strategies (e.g., [CLS], mean-pooling) and existing deep-layer weighting schemes because it preserves low-level linguistic constraints while enhancing high-level abstraction. Moreover, since the syntactic guidance is derived internally without external parsing tools, the method remains scalable and adaptable to low-resource languages and domains. By bridging the gap between syntax and semantics within the internal dynamics of transformers, this work contributes a principled, interpretable, and effective framework for building more linguistically aware representations.",
