  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces a novel framework named 'Recursive Cross-Layer Alignment Network' (ReCLAN), designed to enhance sentence representation quality in transformer models by enabling dynamic, iterative interaction between shallow and deep layer embeddings through a differentiable alignment loop. Unlike prior methods that perform one-time aggregation or static weighting, ReCLAN treats the fusion of syntactic and semantic information as a process of mutual refinement, where early-layer structural patterns and late-layer abstract meanings continuously inform and correct each other over multiple computational steps. At the core of ReCLAN is a learnable alignment cell that operates across designated shallow (e.g., layers 2–4) and deep (e.g., layers 9–12) blocks of a pre-trained transformer such as BERT or RoBERTa. In each iteration, the cell computes dual reconstruction objectives: (1) a syntax-aware objective that induces latent dependency structures from shallow activations using a differentiable parser head, and (2) a semantics-aware objective that predicts contextualized meaning representations (e.g., SRL frames or discourse roles) from deep layers. These two streams are connected via bidirectional projection modules that map both sets of embeddings into a shared latent space, allowing gradient flow from semantic errors to influence syntactic re-parsing and vice versa. A gating mechanism controls the number of refinement steps, terminating when changes in embedding similarity fall below a threshold (learned end-state). The final sentence embedding is derived from the stabilized deep-layer outputs after convergence. To further strengthen coherence, we introduce a multi-reference semantic consistency loss during fine-tuning, inspired by data augmentation techniques in sentence fusion tasks—this encourages the model to recognize semantically equivalent phrasings even under syntactic variation. ReCLAN is trained end-to-end with a composite loss combining task performance (e.g., classification accuracy), syntactic plausibility (measured via induced tree depth and branching entropy), and semantic diversity matching. This framework significantly advances beyond existing approaches by modeling cross-layer integration as an adaptive, stateful process rather than a fixed transformation. It enables transformers to dynamically recalibrate their internal representations based on global context, leading to more robust, interpretable, and linguistically grounded sentence encoders. We expect ReCLAN to excel in tasks requiring deep understanding of both form and meaning—such as discourse analysis, paraphrase detection, and low-data transfer—where rigid architectures fail. Moreover, since no external syntactic tools are used, ReCLAN remains fully self-contained and deployable across languages and domains.",
